interpretation_text:
The patient’s CGM data demonstrate suboptimal glycemic control, with a markedly elevated mean glucose of 208 mg/dL (GMI 8.29%) and significant glycemic variability (SD 121.5 mg/dL, CV 58.4%). Time in range is low at 21.1%, with excessive time spent both above (56.8%) and below (22.1%) target glucose levels. There is a high frequency of hypoglycemia events (191 total, 66 nocturnal) and hyperglycemia events (491), with evidence of the dawn phenomenon and 24 postprandial spikes.

Abnormal patterns include frequent and significant nocturnal hypoglycemia, recurrent postprandial hyperglycemic excursions, and pronounced dawn phenomenon, all contributing to high glycemic variability.

Recommendations: Intensify glucose control to increase time in range and reduce both hypo- and hyperglycemia. Reassess overnight basal insulin dosing to minimize nocturnal hypoglycemia. Review the patient’s hypoglycemia awareness and carbohydrate intake. Address elevated glycemic variability by optimizing basal-bolus dosing and meal timing. Investigate causes of postprandial spikes, including possible missed boluses or carbohydrate misestimation. Adjust basal insulin regimen or consider split dosing to address the dawn phenomenon.
